  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN224">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>aruppam pēṇā tamarkaṭan tatūun</l>
<l>tuṇaipuṇa rāyamoṭu tacumpuṭaṉ ṟolaicci</l>
<l>yirumpā ṇokkaṟ kaṭumpupuran tatūu</l>
<l>maṟamaṟak kaṇṭa neṟimā ṇavaiyattu</l>
<l>muṟainaṟ kaṟiyunar muṉṉuṟap pukaḻnta</l>
<l>tūviyaṟ koḷkait tukaḷaṟu makaḷiroṭu</l>
<l>pariti yuruviṟ palpaṭaip puricai</l>
<l>yeruvai nukarcci yūpa neṭuntūṇ</l>
<l>vēta vēḷvit toḻiṉmuṭit tatūu</l>
<l>maṟintōṉ maṉṟa vaṟivuṭai yāḷa</l>
<l>ṉiṟantōṉ ṟāṉē yaḷittiv vulaka</l>
<l>maruvi māṟi yañcuvarak kaṭukip</l>
<l>peruvaṟaṅ kūrnta vēṉiṟ kālaip</l>
<l>pacitta vāyattup payaṉirai tarumār</l>
<l>pūvāṭ kōvalar pūvuṭa ṉutirak</l>
<l>koytukaṭ ṭaḻitta vēṅkaiyiṉ</l>
<l>melliyaṉ makaḷiru miḻaikaḷain taṉarē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>He was one indeed who knew (10ab)</l>
<l>of winning battles, not heeding fortresses, (1)</l>
<l>of destroying pots together with the united group of companions, (2)</l>
<l>[and] protecting the relatives orf large bardic kinfolk, (3)</l>
<l>and of completing the work of Vedic sacrifices (9)</l>
<l>with the large posts of sacrificial poles, to the enjoyment of the kites, (8)</l>
<l>in fortifications with many armies of circle-shape, (7)</l>
<l>along with speckless women of pure-natured priciples (6)</l>
<l>who are praise, while having in front those who well know the ways (5)</l>
<l>of the assembly glorious for [its] path that fully saw dharma, (4) </l>
<l>	the knowledgable man. (10cd)</l>
<l>He now is one who passed away. Pitiable is the world. (11)</l>
<l>Like kino trees, [their] loads destroyed by plucking, (16)</l>
<l>while the flowers all drop off on account of the cowherds with flower sickles, (15)</l>
<l>in order to give [food] to the yielding rows of the famished herd, (14)</l>
<l>in summer time that abounds in big droughts, (13)</l>
<l>frighteningly coming near, as the waterfalls change, (12)</l>
<l>soft-natured women [now] removed [their] jewels. (17)</l>
</lg>
